  "prompt": "Why astronauts have a white and an orange-coloured space suit?",
  "response": "Astronauts have different space suits for different purposes, and the colors\u2014white and orange\u2014are designed for specific functions and environments.\n\n### **White Space Suit (Extravehicular Mobility Unit - EMU):**\n- **Purpose:** Used for **spacewalks (Extravehicular Activities - EVAs)** outside the spacecraft or space station.\n- **Color Reason:** \n  - **Reflectivity:** White reflects sunlight, helping to regulate the astronaut's body temperature in the extreme conditions of space. Temperatures in space can vary drastically between intense sunlight and the cold of shadow.\n  - **Visibility:** The bright white color makes astronauts easier to see against the blackness of space, which is important for their safety.\n- **Design Features:** The EMU is bulky, heavily insulated, and includes life support systems to provide oxygen, remove carbon dioxide, and maintain pressure.\n\n### **Orange Space Suit (Advanced Crew Escape Suit - ACES):**\n- **Purpose:** Worn during **launch and re-entry** phases of spaceflight.\n- **Color Reason:** \n  - **Safety and Visibility:** The bright orange color is highly visible against the blue ocean and sky, making it easier for rescue teams to locate astronauts in case of an emergency landing.\n  - **Functional Design:** The ACES is lighter and less bulky than the EMU, designed for use inside the spacecraft during critical phases of flight.\n- **Design Features:** The ACES includes a parachute harness, life raft, and survival gear in case of a water landing.\n\n### Summary:\n- **White suits** are for spacewalks, optimized for thermal control and visibility in space.\n- **Orange suits** are for launch and re-entry, optimized for emergency visibility and safety.\n\nEach suit is tailored to the specific challenges of different phases of spaceflight.",
